The expert human took 70 minutes to annotate 16 tasks.We report execution lengths in Table               II             .It shows that         \method        performance quite close to an expert written subgoals.We also ask human unfamiliar with PDDL to annotate these tasks with natural language subgoals, however, a non-expert human found it quite challenging to write subgoals for these symbolic domains.

references: We compare           \method          against single agent and multi-agent PDDL planning for all the above domains. To enable multi-agent planning for symbolic domains, we edited PDDL domain and problem files to reflect multiple agents.We added ‘agent’ parameter to all the actions and agent-specific predicates in the domain, and initialized 2 agents along with their initial states in the prolem files of 20 tasks. This extension requires understanding of PDDL functioning. Moreover, initializing another agent increases the number of possible actions at any state as well introduces addition state conditions, leading to larger search space.We also define 4 long-horizon tasks and their corresponding PDDL problem files for our evaluations in the simulated domain, as shown in Table                  III                . Some objects may also be inside another containers like drawers/cabinetes as per the PDDL initial state specification, making the resultant plans longer. We will open-source our defined domain and problem files.We consider the following approaches for the above domains,

TwoStep advantages generalization to temporal simulation setting without temporal awareness.        We report         AI2THOR        planning time results in Table               III             and and execution length in Table               III             for the 3 approaches.Planning time results show that both         SA PDDL        and         MA PDDL        take a long time to plan and don’t converge quickly.         SA PDDL        has a large goal with several goal conditions to achieve, and         MA PDDL        additionally has added state space complexity due to an additional agent.In execution length,         SA PDDL        has no variance.         MA PDDL        and         \method        have variance in length due to random initialization of agent start location as well as random deadlock release methodology.The deadlocks also cause         \method        to be not achieve lower execution length than         SA PDDL        as they add additional coordination steps.Moreover,         MA PDDL        suffers a lot more with this problem, as it tries to utilize both agents back and forth, while         \method        only splits the problem with one subgoal.
